#### subset samples so that there is an equal number of cancer and control samples ####
dataPrimary_Target <- TCGAquery_SampleTypes(barcode = CaseInfo$cases, typesample = "TP") # primary tumor
dataNormal_Target <- TCGAquery_SampleTypes(barcode = CaseInfo$cases, typesample = "NT") # normal tissue
dataPrimary_Target <- dataPrimary_Target[1:113]
dataNormal_Target <- dataNormal_Target[1:113]
#### downloaded samples of interest ####
TargetSamples <- GDCquery(project = "TCGA-BRCA",
                          data.category = "Transcriptome Profiling",
                          data.type = "Gene Expression Quantification",
                          workflow.type = "STAR - Counts",
                          barcode = c(dataPrimary_Target, dataNormal_Target))
#### Download the data 
GDCdownload(TargetSamples)

data<-GDCprepare(TargetSamples)

This code explores possible clinical correlations between continuous variables in the data set, between one continuous and one categorical variable and between two categorical variables.

As expected, and performed merely for QC, there is an almost perfect positive correlation between days to birth (patient age) and year of birth. There was a moderate positive correlation between days to sample collection and days to death, meaning that the longer it took to take the sample, the longer the period of time the patient remained alive. While this is interesting, it probably isnt a confounding variable. It could potentially indicate the level of physician suspicion of severity of tumor. There is no correlation between year of birth and days to death nor age at diagnosis and days to death. This tells us that older age itself was not correlated to the length of time a patient remained alive after diagnosis nor was being older at the time of diagnosis correlated with time to death after diagnosis. However, there was a significant difference in the mean between vital statuses by age at diagnosis (p=.049). This indicates that the younger the patient was at diagnosis, the more likely they were to still be alive. I also evaluated the relationship between age at diagnosis and tumor status. A histogram was used to visualize the median age for the normal tissue vs.tumor tissue groups. A follow-up t-test found no significant difference between the two means, indicating age not to be a confounding variable for the outcome. Finally, I looked at the realtionship between race and outcome. The barplot shows the distribution of race by tissue type (normal vs.tumor). A subsequent Fisher test was run to look for a significant difference in the distribution. Fisher was chosen because some of the observations are quite low (other with normal tissue = 7). There was a significant difference between white and other races in the number of samples with normal vs.tumor tissue. Given that gene expression and race are both associated with outcome, I may need to include race in further models. I will test that in following sections.

This code calculates the correlations between genes in the data set, and plots the distribution of correlations. Most of the correlations are distributed in the low to no correlation range. Next, the gene pairs that have correlations above .80 and below -.80 are stored in a matrix and then the matrix is converted to a dataframe that is subset for only the unique gene correlation pairs. There are 39,980 unique positive gene pair correlations >.80 and only one negative correlation < -.80 in the data set. .80 was chosen as this is an accepted level corresponding to strong correlation. This information will be important when considering how many genes to add to a model. Genes with high correlation will likely not add much more information to the model over and above each other, and correlation between model genes should be assessed.

# threshold for correlations
threshold <- 0.8

# Create an empty list to store correlated gene pairs
correlated_gene_pairs <- list()

# Loop through the correlation matrix and identify correlated gene pairs
for (i in 1:(ncol(ge.cor) - 1)) {
  for (j in (i + 1):ncol(ge.cor)) {
    if (ge.cor[i, j] > threshold || ge.cor[i, j] < -threshold) {
      correlated_gene_pairs <- append(correlated_gene_pairs, list(c(rownames(ge.cor)[i], rownames(ge.cor)[j],ge.cor[i,j])))
    }
  }
}

  pr.ge.cor[i,2]<-correlated_gene_pairs[[i]][[2]]
  pr.ge.cor[i,3]<-correlated_gene_pairs[[i]][[3]]

Variance

The variance in gene expression was explored for the differentially expressed genes. The histogram shows the distribution of variances and indicates that there is a moderate amount of expression variance for most genes, with a small fraction having a large amount of variance and a small fraction having only a small amount. Also shown below are the names of the ten genes with highest expression variance and names of the ten genes with the lowest expression variance.

It is important to look at variance in the gene expression data prior to model building to see if there is any real change in expression for any of the genes. Stable expression levels would indicate that gene expression may have nothing to do with the outcome of interest. It is also important to look at variance so that you can stabilize the variance if it is too large. Even after quantile normalization, the variance in the dataset was large, so further analyses in models are performed on log2(datapt.+1) transformed data.

One way to select genes to use in a model could be by looking at the genes with the most variance, based on the assumption that the genes with the highest variance are more likely to be associated with the outcome. However, it is probably better to test which genes are more closely associated with the outcome rather than to just assume based on variance. Choosing the top x number of genes with the most variance can help in exploratory analyses such as Principal Component Analyses if the full set of genes (including low variance genes) introduces too much noise into the data to be able to get any meaningful clustering.

Ultimately, gene selection should include an analysis of the genes whose expression changes most closely relate to tumor status (normal vs.tumor tissue) and an analysis of how closely correlated the genes are with each other. These values can then be entered into a forward selection process to get a more heterogeneous subset of genes that are all more likely to independently affect the outcome. This process could be forward or backward selection.

Initial Model

Before developing other models, I started with logistic regression of just the most significant gene, ENSG00000158966.16, to predict the outcome of disease or no disease. This model performed quite well, even on cross-validation, with 93% accuracy, 96% sensitivity and specificity and only 3% false positive rate. While this model may be difficult to beat since it is both simple and highly accurate, sensitive and specific, it is worth testing other models to see if we can predict with closer to 100% success.

Since both expression of ENSG00000158966.16 and race were significantly associated with outcome, I wanted to test for an additive or interaction effect on the outcome. When including race into the logistic model with gene expression, race was no longer significant and no interaction or additive effect was observed. It is possible that gene expression explains most of the variance in the outcome and that race does not add much more toward that explanation. While there was a significant racial difference in gene expression for this gene, the logistic regression results suggest that this difference doesnt significantly impact the likelihood of tumor when accounting for gene expression. Therefore, I will move forward with model construction without utilizing race as a variable in predicting tumor vs.normal tissue samples.

do.check=function(data,model) {
  if ( is.null(data) ) { stop("New data must be specified") }
  if ( is.null(model) ) {
    stop("The model has not been trained yet!")}}

predictor.LR = list(
  model = NULL,
  train = function(f,data,...) {
    
    predictor.LR$model <<- glm(f, data,
                               family="binomial",na.action="na.exclude",...)
  },
  predict=function(newdata=NULL) {
    do.check(newdata,predictor.LR$model)
    as.numeric(
      predict(predictor.LR$model,newdata,type="response") > 0.5
    )
  }
)

#bring in prediction metric assessment for LR
assess.prediction=function(truth,predicted) {
  predicted = predicted[ ! is.na(truth) ]
  truth = truth[ ! is.na(truth) ]
  truth = truth[ ! is.na(predicted) ]
  predicted = predicted[ ! is.na(predicted) ]
  cat("Total cases that are not NA: ",length(truth),"\n",sep="")
  cat("Correct predictions (accuracy): ",sum(truth==predicted), "(",signif(sum(truth==predicted)*100/length(truth),3),"%)\n",sep="")
  TP = sum(truth==1 & predicted==1)
  TN = sum(truth==0 & predicted==0)
  FP = sum(truth==0 & predicted==1)
  FN = sum(truth==1 & predicted==0)
  P = TP+FN 
  N = FP+TN 
  cat("TPR (sensitivity)=TP/P: ", signif(100*TP/P,3),"%\n",sep="")
  cat("TNR (specificity)=TN/N: ", signif(100*TN/N,3),"%\n",sep="")
  cat("PPV (precision)=TP/(TP+FP): ", signif(100*TP/(TP+FP),3),"%\n",sep="")
  cat("FDR (false discovery)=1-PPV: ", signif(100*FP/(TP+FP),3),"%\n",sep="")
  cat("FPR =FP/N=1-TNR: ", signif(100*FP/N,3),"%\n",sep="")
}

#cross-validation for LR
cross.validate=function(predictor,formula,data=NULL,
                        method="random", N=100, n.out=5,...) {
  if ( is.null(data) ) { stop("data must be specified") }
  f.str = deparse(formula)
  dependent.name = sub("\\s*~.*","",f.str)
  if ( ! dependent.name %in% names(data) ) {
    dependent.data = get(dependent.name,envir=environment(formula))
    data=cbind(dependent.data,data)
    names(data)[1] = dependent.name
  } else {
    ind = match(dependent.name,names(data))
    data = cbind( data[,ind,drop=F],data[,-ind,drop=F] )
  }
  
  truth = data[,dependent.name] 
  truth = truth[0] 
  prediction=numeric()
  for ( i in 1:N ) {
    leave.out = sample(nrow(data),size=n.out)
    training.data = data[-leave.out,,drop=F]
    test.data = data[leave.out,,drop=F]
    predictor$train(formula , data=training.data,...)
    pred=predictor$predict(test.data[,-1,drop=F])
    truth[ (length(truth)+1):(length(truth)+n.out) ] =
      test.data[,dependent.name]
    prediction = c(prediction, pred)
  }
  list(truth=truth,prediction=prediction)
}

cv.LR.1=cross.validate(predictor.LR, tumor.stat.1 ~ ENSG00000158966.16,data=top.de.tumor )
assess.prediction(cv.LR.1$truth,cv.LR.1$prediction)

Variable Selection

The code below outlines the forward selection process for selecting 2,3,5 and 10 genes to include in the models. The process considers both gene expression correlation with outcome and gene expression correlation between genes. p-values from differential gene expression are used to determine gene expression correlation with tumor status. Since the outcome is binary (tumor or not), a pseudo-correlation technique was used to transform t-test p-values to correlation coefficient scale. The forward selection process below first chooses the gene with the most correlation to the outcome, and then begins selecting the next genes by considering gene-gene correlation as well as correlation to outcome in order to obtain a set of genes that are more likely to be independently influencing the outcome and are adding value to the predictive ability of the model.

#Variable selection-----------
#Using forward selection to avoid getting only the genes most correlated with the outcome and with each other

term1 = corrs.to.outcome

  selected = which.max(corrs.to.outcome)
  for ( j in 1:(N[i]-1) ) {

Models

Logistic Regression

I first developed logistic regression models for the 2, 3, and 5 forward selected genes. The only model that would converge was the 2 gene model. This model performed with 95.8% accuracy, 96% sensitivity and 95.4% specificity. FDR was 4%. While the 3 and 5 gene models were better predictors, I would not move forward with these models as they failed to converge.

}

Neural Network Models

I developed neural network models for the 2, 3, and 5 forward selected genes. Within neural network models, the hidden node, hidden layer and activation function parameters can be tuned. Since the output node here is binary, the models were set to utilize the sigmoid function. Based on the results of my initial logistic regression model of gene CACHD1, I dont expect to need an overly complex neural network model, and therefore developed my models with just 1 hidden layer. Models with fewer hidden nodes are simpler, and with so few input nodes, I chose to start by including just 0 hidden nodes in each model. For the 2 gene model, I started with 0 hidden nodes and also tried 1 hidden node. The model with zero hidden nodes was slightly more accurate and had lower false postives, and that is the model included here. For the 3 gene model, I started with 0 hidden nodes and progressed up to 5 nodes. The most accurate, specific and sensitive model was developed with 4 hidden nodes, and 5 hidden nodes did not increase predictive ability further. The 4 node model is included here. Finally, for the 5 gene model, I started with 0 hidden nodes and progressed to 6 nodes, with the best performing model at 5 nodes. This model did not perform significantly better than the 3 gene model. Therefore, it does not seem that building a model with more genes would be beneficial.

Overall, the three forward selected gene neural network model performed the best with lower complexity than the five forward selected gene neural network model and with better performance metrics than the two gene model. However, despite running 1000 iterations of cross-validation on test data, I would be a little concerned that the number of hidden nodes included in that model would be overfitting the current data set.

library(neuralnet)
expand.formula = function(f,data=NULL) {
  f.str = deparse(f)
  if ( grepl("\\.$",f.str)[1] ) {
    if ( is.null(data) ) { stop("Shortcut formula ~. requires a dataframe") }
  } else {
    return(f)
  }
  dependent.name = sub("\\s*~.*","",f.str)
  n = names(data) 
  n = n[ n != dependent.name ]
  rhs = paste(n,collapse=" + ")
  f.str = sub("\\.$",rhs,f.str)
  f = as.formula(f.str,env=environment(f))
  return(f)
}

do.check=function(data,model) {
  if ( is.null(data) ) { stop("New data must be specified") }
  if ( is.null(model) ) {
    stop("The model has not been trained yet!")}}

predictor.NN = list(
  model = NULL,
  train = function(f,data,...) {
    
    predictor.NN$model <<- {
      f = expand.formula(f,data)
      f.str = deparse(f)
      f.str = paste(f.str,collapse="")
      dependent.name = sub("\\s*~.*","",f.str)
      if ( ! dependent.name %in% names(data) ) {
        dependent.data = get(dependent.name,envir=environment(f))
        data=cbind(dependent.data,data)
        names(data)[1] = dependent.name
      }
      has.na = apply(data,1,function(x) { any(is.na(x)) } )
      data = data[! has.na,,drop=F]
      if ( is.factor( data[,dependent.name] ) ) {
        data[,dependent.name] = as.numeric(as.vector(data[,dependent.name]))
      }
      neuralnet(f,data,...)
    }
  },
  predict=function(newdata=NULL) {
    do.check(newdata,predictor.NN$model)
    as.numeric(
      predict(predictor.NN$model,newdata,type="response") > 0.5
    )
  }
)

#bring in prediction metric assessment for NN
assess.prediction=function(truth,predicted) {
  predicted = predicted[ ! is.na(truth) ]
  truth = truth[ ! is.na(truth) ]
  truth = truth[ ! is.na(predicted) ]
  predicted = predicted[ ! is.na(predicted) ]
  cat("Total cases that are not NA: ",length(truth),"\n",sep="")
  cat("Correct predictions (accuracy): ",sum(truth==predicted), "(",signif(sum(truth==predicted)*100/length(truth),3),"%)\n",sep="")
  TP = sum(truth==1 & predicted==1)
  TN = sum(truth==0 & predicted==0)
  FP = sum(truth==0 & predicted==1)
  FN = sum(truth==1 & predicted==0)
  P = TP+FN 
  N = FP+TN 
  cat("TPR (sensitivity)=TP/P: ", signif(100*TP/P,3),"%\n",sep="")
  cat("TNR (specificity)=TN/N: ", signif(100*TN/N,3),"%\n",sep="")
  cat("PPV (precision)=TP/(TP+FP): ", signif(100*TP/(TP+FP),3),"%\n",sep="")
  cat("FDR (false discovery)=1-PPV: ", signif(100*FP/(TP+FP),3),"%\n",sep="")
  cat("FPR =FP/N=1-TNR: ", signif(100*FP/N,3),"%\n",sep="")
}

#cross-validation for NN
cross.validate=function(predictor,formula,data=NULL,
                        method="random", N=100, n.out=5,...) {
  if ( is.null(data) ) { stop("data must be specified") }
  f.str = deparse(formula)
  dependent.name = sub("\\s*~.*","",f.str)
  if ( ! dependent.name %in% names(data) ) {
    dependent.data = get(dependent.name,envir=environment(formula))
    data=cbind(dependent.data,data)
    names(data)[1] = dependent.name
  } else {
    ind = match(dependent.name,names(data))
    data = cbind( data[,ind,drop=F],data[,-ind,drop=F] )
  }
  
  truth = data[,dependent.name] 
  truth = truth[0] 
  prediction=numeric()
  for ( i in 1:N ) {
    leave.out = sample(nrow(data),size=n.out)
    training.data = data[-leave.out,,drop=F]
    test.data = data[leave.out,,drop=F]
    predictor$train(formula , data=training.data,...)
    pred=predictor$predict(test.data[,-1,drop=F])
    truth[ (length(truth)+1):(length(truth)+n.out) ] =
      test.data[,dependent.name]
    prediction = c(prediction, pred)
  }
  list(truth=truth,prediction=prediction)
}

Random Forest

I developed random forest models for the 2, 3, and 5 forward selected genes. Within random forest models, the mtry parameter can be tuned. Based on the results of my initial logistic regression model of gene CACHD1, I dont expect to need an overly complex random forest model, and therefore developed my models starting with mtry=1. Models with fewer mtry splits are simpler and can be more generalizable. For all models, I started with mtry=1 and progressed to mtry=2. Each models performance was worse on mtry=2 so all included models here are the mtry=1 models. The three gene model improved performance over the two gene model, but the five gene model did not further improve upon the three gene model enough to justify the increased complexity. Therefore, it does not seem that building a model with more genes would be beneficial.

Overall, the three forward selected gene random forest model performed the best with lower complexity than the five forward selected gene random forest model and with better performance metrics than the two gene model.

}

Support Vector Machine (SVM)

I developed SVM models for the 2, 3, and 5 forward selected genes. Within SVM models, the first parameter to tune is the kernel and then tune other parameters as necessary based on kernel selection. Given the success of the logistic regression model with just CACHD1, I started with the linear kernel, but did try the radial and polynomial kernels as well. The linear and radial kernels performed very similarly, with the polynomial kernel performing much worse, which was not surprising. This data is linear in nature, and therefore I settled on the linear kernel. Since a linear kernel was chosen, the only other parameter I set was the cost. Smaller costs are more generalizable but may underfit the data. Here, I started with the default cost = 1, and experimented with lower cost values (.10, .01). The default value of 1 resulted in models with best predictive capability. The three gene model improved performance over the two gene model, and this time the five gene model did further improve upon the three gene model enough to justify increased complexity. I tried a 10 gene model to see if adding more genes would be worth it, but this model performed worse than the 5 gene model.

Overall, the five forward selected gene SVM model performed the best. With an accuracy,sensitivity and specificity of 99% and FDR of only .7%, the increase in complexity here is worth the trade-off of the simpler 3 gene model. This model reached almost 100% accuracy!

library(e1071)

predictor.svm = list(
  model = NULL,
  train = function(f,data,g,...) {
    predictor.svm$model <<- svm(f,data,kernel="linear",cost=1)
  },
  predict=function(newdata=NULL) {
    # check that we got data and that the model was already trained:
    do.check(newdata,predictor.svm$model)
    # here we wrap the specifics of predicting with LR: the original
    # predict would return the probabilities, so we have to apply the
    # decision cutoff and convert to numeric in order to get predicted
    # classes. All these gory details are hidden in this wrapper:
    as.numeric(as.character(predict(predictor.svm$model,newdata))
    )
  }
)
assess.prediction=function(truth,predicted) {
  # check for missing values (we are going to compute metrics
  # on non-missing values of course)
  predicted = predicted[ ! is.na(truth) ]
  truth = truth[ ! is.na(truth) ]
  truth = truth[ ! is.na(predicted) ]
  predicted = predicted[ ! is.na(predicted) ]
  cat("Total cases that are not NA: ",length(truth),"\n",sep="")
  # overall accuracy of the test: how many cases (both positive and
  # negative) we got right:
  cat("Correct predictions (accuracy): ",sum(truth==predicted), "(",signif(sum(truth==predicted)*100/length(truth),3),"%)\n",sep="")
  # how predictions align against known training/testing outcomes:
  # TP/FP= true/false positives, TN/FN=true/false negatives:
  TP = sum(truth==1 & predicted==1)
  TN = sum(truth==0 & predicted==0)
  FP = sum(truth==0 & predicted==1)
  FN = sum(truth==1 & predicted==0)
  P = TP+FN # total number of positives in the truth data
  N = FP+TN # total number of negatives
  cat("TPR (sensitivity)=TP/P: ", signif(100*TP/P,3),"%\n",sep="")
  cat("TNR (specificity)=TN/N: ", signif(100*TN/N,3),"%\n",sep="")
  cat("PPV (precision)=TP/(TP+FP): ", signif(100*TP/(TP+FP),3),"%\n",sep="")
  cat("FDR (false discovery)=1-PPV: ", signif(100*FP/(TP+FP),3),"%\n",sep="")
  cat("FPR =FP/N=1-TNR: ", signif(100*FP/N,3),"%\n",sep="")
}

Conclusion

All of the models below outperformed the original single gene model based on the most significantly differentially expressed gene, ENSG00000158966.16. The two best performing models are the SVM and NN models. Depending on the training/testing data sets, the SVM 5 gene model can reach over 99% accuracy with FDR <1% and 98% sensitivity and specificity, using a linear kernel. The Neural Network 3 gene model can reach over 98% accuracy with FDR around 2% with 4 hidden nodes. Both models need to be further validated on new test data, but the SVM model with the linear kernel is likely to be the simpler model and less prone to over-fitting than the neural network model. This makes the SVM model a more favorable one.

Below, I looked at the genes that were in the included in the models as well as the 3 genes most closely associated to the outcome. The 5 forward selected genes are lesser known in breast cancer, but appear to have been associated with breast cancer in various studies. Of the top 3 significant genes, both SPRY2 and EGFR are widely known to be associated with breast cancer. Decreased expression of SPRY2 is associated with tumor development and metastasis (Dai et al., 2023) and increased expression of EGFR is related to poorer prognosis in breast cancer (Masuda et al., 2012). In this study, EGFR is downregulated in tumor tissue, and this difference could be followed up in further studies. The role of the most significant gene ,CACHD1, is not well described in breast cancer at this time.

Finally, given the strong involvement of SPRY2 in breast cancer, I developed one last model involving that gene. Since the correlation between the top 3 genes is almost 1, I did not build a model with all of these together. The SPRY2 model performed quite well, with 98% accuracy, 97% sensitivity, 98% specificity and 1.6% FDR. This model is the simplest model of all, and it would be interesting to see if it outperforms the SVM model on further experimental data sets.

Dai, H., Xu, W., Wang, L.et al.Loss of SPRY2 contributes to cancer-associated fibroblasts activation and promotes breast cancer development.Breast Cancer Res25, 90 (2023). https://doi.org/10.1186/s13058-023-01683-8

Masuda H, Zhang D, Bartholomeusz C, Doihara H, Hortobagyi GN, Ueno NT. Role of epidermal growth factor receptor in breast cancer.Breast Cancer Res Treat. 2012;136(2):331-345. doi:10.1007/s10549-012-2289-9

#SPRY2 model
do.check=function(data,model) {
  if ( is.null(data) ) { stop("New data must be specified") }
  if ( is.null(model) ) {
    stop("The model has not been trained yet!")}}

predictor.LR = list(
  model = NULL,
  train = function(f,data,...) {
    
    predictor.LR$model <<- glm(f, data,
                               family="binomial",na.action="na.exclude",...)
  },
  predict=function(newdata=NULL) {
    do.check(newdata,predictor.LR$model)
    as.numeric(
      predict(predictor.LR$model,newdata,type="response") > 0.5
    )
  }
)

#bring in prediction metric assessment for LR
assess.prediction=function(truth,predicted) {
  predicted = predicted[ ! is.na(truth) ]
  truth = truth[ ! is.na(truth) ]
  truth = truth[ ! is.na(predicted) ]
  predicted = predicted[ ! is.na(predicted) ]
  cat("Total cases that are not NA: ",length(truth),"\n",sep="")
  cat("Correct predictions (accuracy): ",sum(truth==predicted), "(",signif(sum(truth==predicted)*100/length(truth),3),"%)\n",sep="")
  TP = sum(truth==1 & predicted==1)
  TN = sum(truth==0 & predicted==0)
  FP = sum(truth==0 & predicted==1)
  FN = sum(truth==1 & predicted==0)
  P = TP+FN 
  N = FP+TN 
  cat("TPR (sensitivity)=TP/P: ", signif(100*TP/P,3),"%\n",sep="")
  cat("TNR (specificity)=TN/N: ", signif(100*TN/N,3),"%\n",sep="")
  cat("PPV (precision)=TP/(TP+FP): ", signif(100*TP/(TP+FP),3),"%\n",sep="")
  cat("FDR (false discovery)=1-PPV: ", signif(100*FP/(TP+FP),3),"%\n",sep="")
  cat("FPR =FP/N=1-TNR: ", signif(100*FP/N,3),"%\n",sep="")
}

#cross-validation for LR
cross.validate=function(predictor,formula,data=NULL,
                        method="random", N=100, n.out=5,...) {
  if ( is.null(data) ) { stop("data must be specified") }
  f.str = deparse(formula)
  dependent.name = sub("\\s*~.*","",f.str)
  if ( ! dependent.name %in% names(data) ) {
    dependent.data = get(dependent.name,envir=environment(formula))
    data=cbind(dependent.data,data)
    names(data)[1] = dependent.name
  } else {
    ind = match(dependent.name,names(data))
    data = cbind( data[,ind,drop=F],data[,-ind,drop=F] )
  }
  
  truth = data[,dependent.name] 
  truth = truth[0] 
  prediction=numeric()
  for ( i in 1:N ) {
    leave.out = sample(nrow(data),size=n.out)
    training.data = data[-leave.out,,drop=F]
    test.data = data[leave.out,,drop=F]
    predictor$train(formula , data=training.data,...)
    pred=predictor$predict(test.data[,-1,drop=F])
    truth[ (length(truth)+1):(length(truth)+n.out) ] =
      test.data[,dependent.name]
    prediction = c(prediction, pred)
  }
  list(truth=truth,prediction=prediction)
}

boxplot(top.de.tumor[,2]~tumor.stat.1,xlab="Tissue type",ylab="Expression of ENSG00000136158.12",col="darkorchid4",cex.lab=.75,names=c("Normal","Tumor"))

cv.LR.1=cross.validate(predictor.LR, tumor.stat.1 ~ ENSG00000136158.12,data=top.de.tumor )
assess.prediction(cv.LR.1$truth,cv.LR.1$prediction)
